<br>
We'll have to take some of these one thing at a time.<br>
<br>
As an instructor one of the hardest things I have to do is &quot;relate&quot; to a student. I can be with a guys like Jared or Gene and they are easy to talk to. Being able to say &quot;you're creeping&quot; or &quot;your grip is too firm&quot; or some other thing like that and the issue is resolved. Jared said that Bill made a comment about the shape of his loops during his CCI test and he immediately adjusted his grip pressure to resolve the loop shape.<br>
<br>
When I am with a total begining student I have difficulty relating to them. It has been nearly 35 years ago that I started to learn to fly cast. Trying to teach someone to stop a rod is a close second to trying to teach my kids how to drink through a straw or blow their nose. I mean how do you &quot;teach&quot; that? They just have to do it??<br>
<br>
Your MOI really helped me with that. We can talk about &quot;specifics if you like but in general you talk about how a student perceives and understands the material they are being given. Much like Bill explaination of what causes tailing loops, it is something that can be demonstrated over and over, regardless of the level of understanding. That is the litmious test of a method. If it can be demonstrated on command then it is a solid fact as far as I'm concerned. Your levels of perception and understanding will work regardless of the experience of the student.<br>
<br>
I &quot;do&quot; think you should submit segments of your MOI to &quot;The Loop&quot;. We can &quot;all&quot; fly cast pretty well here. Our real weakness is the teaching method.<br>
<br>
After reading your MOI I certianly became more interested in establising some terms that are consistant in the Federation. At least we would all be teaching the same vocabulary even if we don't teach the same &quot;style&quot;.<br>
<br>
John<br>
